<TITLE> Cabinet clears 20 new laws </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 23 (bdnews24.com)  The cabinet cleared Monday 20 new laws including the ones on consumer protection, information rights, human rights and taxation for parliament to pass, the prime minister's press secretary said. Abul Kalam Azad said a tax law and a consumer rights protection law were among the new acts given approval. The National Board of Revenue Ordinance 2008 was repealed to make way for the National Board of Revenue (Amendment) Act 2009, Azad said. A cabinet meeting, chaired by prime minister Sheikh Hasina, also approved the Consumer Rights Protection Act 2009. "The Trade Corporation of Bangladesh will be strengthened. To keep price of products stable for consumers, essentials will be imported through TCB," he quoted Hasina as saying. The other laws approved were Bangladesh Biman Corporation (Amendment-1) Act 2009, Upazila Parishad Act 2009 by amending Upazila Parishad Act 1998, Bangladesh Telegraph and Telephone Board (Amendment) Act 2009, Dhaka Electricity Supply Authority (Amendment) Act 2009, Right to Information Act 2009, Mobile Court Act 2009, Government Finance and Budget Management Act 2009, Bangladesh Flag Vessel (Protection) (Amendment) Act 2009 and Bangladesh Shilpa Bank (Amendment) Act 2009. Also approved were The President's (remuneration and privileges) (amendment) Act 2009, Islamic University (Amendment) Act 2009, Supreme Court Judges (remuneration and privileges) (Amendment) Act 2009, Bangladesh Laws (revision and declaration) (Amendment) Act 2009, National Human Rights Commission Act 2009, Gram Sarkar (repeal) Act 2009, Local Government (city corporation) Act 2009 and Local Government (municipal) Act 2009. The Code of Criminal Procedure (Amendment) Act 2009 has been returned and the Grameen Bank (Amendment) Act 2009 will be presented again at the next cabinet session with certain corrections, said Azad. Power secretary Nasiruddin Ahmed, presenting the DESA Amendment Act, told the prime minister that 130 megawatts had been added to the national grid since the present government came to power, Azad said. He also said the power secretary was optimistic about adding an additional 700 megawatt to the grid by June. The prime minister directed the officials to make sure that farmers get uninterrupted water supply for the next irrigation season, the press secretary added. bdnews24.
